# Orchestrate — for claude-code

This skill is built for **claude-code**. If you are not claude-code, do not
follow its instructions.

## Delegate or not

Taste stays with you: naming, API shape, and UX copy are yours to decide.
Anti-signals for a GPT-5.5 offload: ambiguous specs, aesthetic judgment.

## Routing

Do not construct commands from this table — read the reference first; it is the contract.
| Dimension | When | Route | Note | Reference |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| Computer-use / runtime verification | launching apps, browser automation, screenshots, simulators | codex/gpt-5.5 |  | [codex](references/codex.md) |
| Bounded implementation | clear-spec, mechanical, bulk changes; worktree-isolated | codex/gpt-5.5 (grok/grok-4.5 fallback) |  | [codex](references/codex.md) |
| Token-heavy read-only investigation | large logs, giant specs/PDFs, screenshot piles | grok/grok-4.5 | offload for parallelism/quota — you are equally strong here | [grok](references/grok.md) |

## Anti-recursion

Never invoke another orchestrator recursively. The provider CLIs are:
claude, codex, grok.

### Workflow wrapper

Wrap a codex run in a worktree, capture its report file, and verify before
relaying — you own the merge.

===== references/codex.md =====

# codex (GPT-5.5)

Drive the Codex CLI for bounded implementation and computer-use verification.
Run implementation in a worktree; state boundaries in the prompt for
computer-use runs.

Anti-recursion: a child must never spawn claude, codex, grok.

===== references/grok.md =====

# grok (grok-4.5)

Headless writes by default; the provider API is the data-egress path. Pass the
prompt via `--prompt-file`; use `--no-subagents` to hold anti-recursion.

Anti-recursion: a child must never spawn claude, codex, grok.
